  "level": 10,
  "topic": "Türkçe Geçmiş Zamanlar (-dı / -di / -du / -dü / -tı / -ti / -tu / -tü & -miş / -mış / -muş / -müş)",
  "language_pair": "en-tr",
  "target_language": "tr",
  "native_language": "en",
  "description": "Turkish Past Tenses – for English speakers. Turkish has two main past tenses: 1. Definite Past (-dı/-di/-du/-dü etc.) for witnessed, certain, completed events you saw or experienced personally. 2. Reported/Evidential Past (-miş/-mış/-muş/-müş) for events you heard from others, inferred, or didn't witness directly. Both are very common – similar to English simple past, but with an important evidential distinction.",
  "grammar_focus": {
    "rule_definite": "Verb stem + -dı / -di / -du / -dü / -tı / -ti / -tu / -tü (vowel harmony & consonant change) + personal ending",
    "rule_reported": "Verb stem + -mış / -mış / -muş / -müş (vowel harmony) + personal ending",
    "suffixes": {
      "ben (I)": "-ım / -im / -um / -üm",
      "sen (you)": "-ın / -in / -un / -ün",
      "o (he/she/it)": "no personal ending",
      "biz (we)": "-ık / -ik / -uk / -ük",
      "siz (you plural)": "-ınız / -iniz / -unuz / -ünüz",
      "onlar (they)": "-lar / -ler"
    },
    "note_en": "Definite past (-dı) = I know it happened because I saw/was there (like English simple past in most cases). Reported past (-miş) = I heard about it / it seems / apparently / I just found out / surprise discovery. Negation: -ma/-me before the past suffix: gitmedim, gitmemişim. Questions: mi/mı/mu/mü after personal ending: Gittin mi? Gitmiş mi?"
  },
